recordings.rmk: Calls from a group of Curlews that were roosting in fields near a freshwater lake on Inishbofin, Co. Galway. The clip features some of the flock preparing to fly off and resume feeding.  The featured call is almost onomatopoeic - 'cur-lew' - and can be delivered once or repeated. One example of repetition is at 0:14. Sometimes the note rises sharply at the end and imparts a sense of unease that is not conveyed when the same note is less inflected. You can hear this difference in panicky versus relaxed  (or shrill versus mellow) if you compare the call at 0:04 with the same note at 0:00. Other species audible are OYSTERCATCHER (best at 0:23), LAPWING (one note at 0:14) and GREENSHANK (0:30 and 0:35).
